Here is a numerical problem for a math student to solve:

A manufacturing company produces three types of products - A, B, and C. The company wants to know if there is a statistically significant difference in the average weights of the products produced by three machines. A random sample of 10 products for each machine is taken, and the weights are recorded as follows: 

Machine 1: {50, 52, 48, 55, 60, 58, 53, 49, 51, 54} 
Machine 2: {46, 49, 45, 47, 50, 48, 53, 44, 42, 51} 
Machine 3: {57, 60, 62, 65, 63, 64, 59, 61, 58, 62} 

Assuming that the weights are normally distributed and that the variances of the three populations are equal, conduct an ANOVA test at a significance level of 0.05 to determine if there is a significant difference in the average weights produced by the three machines.
